%T A396897 4,7,18,1,4,9,20,1,21,1,16,15,4,1,24,7,20,9,16,1,27,11,28,9,4,1,30,1,
%U A396897 4,21,32,13,33,1,16,9,28,1,36,1,4,25,16,11,36,1,40,27
%N A396897 a(n) = n divided by the largest ratio of consecutive divisors of n.
%C A396897 a(n) is always a positive integer: if d_{i+1}/d_i is the maximal ratio of consecutive divisors, then a(n) = (n/d_{i+1})*d_i, which is an integer since d_{i+1} divides n.
%F A396897 a(n) = n / max_i (d_{i+1}/d_i), where 1 = d_1 < ... < d_t = n are the divisors of n.
%F A396897 a(p) = 1 for prime p.
%F A396897 For squarefree n = p_1*p_2*...*p_k with p_1 < ... < p_k, a(n) = min_{0<=j<=k-1} (n/p_{j+1}) * Product_{i=1..j} p_i.
%e A396897 For n = 10 the divisors are 1, 2, 5, 10, with consecutive ratios 2, 5/2, 2; the largest is 5/2, so a(10) = 10/(5/2) = 4.
%e A396897 For n = 12 the divisors are 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 12, with largest consecutive ratio 2, so a(12) = 12/2 = 6.
%t A396897 a[n_]:=With[{d=Divisors[n]},n/Max[Rest[d]/Most[d]]]; Array[a,80,2]
%o A396897 (PARI) a(n)=my(d=divisors(n)); n/vecmax(vector(#d-1,i,d[i+1]/d[i]));
